[1319.190088, "o", "\u001b[?1049h\u001b[22;0;0t\u001b[24;1H\u001b[?1h\u001b=\r"]
[1319.207965, "o", "\u001b[4mUSERADD\u001b[24m(8)               System Management Commands               \u001b[4mUSERADD\u001b[24m(8)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       useradd - create a new user or update default new user information\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22m[\u001b[4moptions\u001b[24m] \u001b[4mLOGIN\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22m-D\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22m-D [\u001b[4moptions\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22mis a low level utility for adding users. On Debian,\u001b[m\r\n       administrators should usually use \u001b[1madduser\u001b[22m(8) instead.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       When invoked without the \u001b[1m-D \u001b[22moption, the \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22mcommand creates a new\u001b[m\r\n       user account using the values specified on the command line plus the\u001b[m\r\n       default values from the system. Depending on command line options,\u001b[m\r\n       the \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22mcommand will update system files and may also create the\u001b[m\r\n       new user's home directory and copy initial files.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1320.252499, "o", "\r\u001b[K       By default, a group will also be created for the new user (see \u001b[1m-g\u001b[22m,\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-N\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m-U\u001b[22m, and \u001b[1mUSERGROUPS_ENAB\u001b[22m).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mOPTIONS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The options which apply to the \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22mcommand are:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--badname\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Allow names that do not conform to standards.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-b\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--base-dir \u001b[4m\u001b[22mBASE_DIR\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           The default base directory for the system if \u001b[1m-d \u001b[4m\u001b[22mHOME_DIR\u001b[24m is not\u001b[m\r\n           specified.  \u001b[4mBASE_DIR\u001b[24m is concatenated with the account name to\u001b[m\r\n           define the home directory.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           If this option is not specified, \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22mwill use the base\u001b[m\r\n           directory specified by the \u001b[1mHOME \u001b[22mvariable in /etc/default/useradd,\u001b[m\r\n           or /home by default.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-c\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--comment \u001b[4m\u001b[22mCOMMENT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Any text string. It is generally a short description of the\u001b[m\r\n           account, and is currently used as the fie"]
[1320.252617, "o", "ld for the user's full\u001b[m\r\n           name.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 24 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1322.189848, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1m-d\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--home-dir \u001b[4m\u001b[22mHOME_DIR\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           The new user will be created using \u001b[4mHOME_DIR\u001b[24m as the value for the\u001b[m\r\n           user's login directory. The default is to append the \u001b[4mLOGIN\u001b[24m name\u001b[m\r\n           to \u001b[4mBASE_DIR\u001b[24m and use that as the login directory name. If the\u001b[m\r\n           directory \u001b[4mHOME_DIR\u001b[24m does not exist, then it will be created unless\u001b[m\r\n           the \u001b[1m-M \u001b[22moption is specified.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-D\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--defaults\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           See below, the subsection \"Changing the default values\".\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-e\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--expiredate \u001b[4m\u001b[22mEXPIRE_DATE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           The date on which the user account will be disabled. The date is\u001b[m\r\n           specified in the format \u001b[4mYYYY-MM-DD\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           If not specified, \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22mwill use the default expiry date\u001b[m\r\n           specified by the \u001b[1mEXPIRE \u001b[22mvariable in /etc/default/useradd, or an\u001b[m\r\n           empty string (no expiry) by default.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-"]
[1322.190112, "o", "f\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--inactive \u001b[4m\u001b[22mINACTIVE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           defines the number of days after the password exceeded its\u001b[m\r\n           maximum age where the user is expected to replace this password.\u001b[m\r\n           The value is stored in the shadow password file. An input of 0\u001b[m\r\n           will disable an expired password with no delay. An input of -1\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 47 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1358.538019, "o", "\r\u001b[K           will blank the respective field in the shadow password file. See\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1mshadow\u001b[22m(5)for more information.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           If not specified, \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22mwill use the default inactivity period\u001b[m\r\n           specified by the \u001b[1mINACTIVE \u001b[22mvariable in /etc/default/useradd, or -1\u001b[m\r\n           by default.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-F\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--add-subids-for-system\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Update /etc/subuid and /etc/subgid even when creating a system\u001b[m\r\n           account with \u001b[1m-r \u001b[22moption.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-g\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--gid \u001b[4m\u001b[22mGROUP\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           The name or the number of the user's primary group. The group\u001b[m\r\n           name must exist. A group number must refer to an already existing\u001b[m\r\n           group.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           If not specified, the behavior of \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22mwill depend on the\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1mUSERGROUPS_ENAB \u001b[22mvariable in /etc/login.defs. If this variable is\u001b[m\r\n           set to \u001b[4myes\u001b[24m (or \u001b[1m-U/--user-group \u001b[22mis specified on the command line),\u001b[m\r\n           a group will be created for the user, with the same name as the\u001b[m\r\n           loginname. If the variable is set to \u001b[4mno\u001b[24m (or \u001b[1m-N/--no-user-group \u001b[22mis\u001b[m\r\n           specified on the command line), useradd will set the primary\u001b[m\r\n           group of the new user to the value specified by the \u001b[1mGROUP\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 70 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1360.613468, "o", "\r\u001b[K           variable in /etc/default/useradd, or 100 by default.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-G\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--groups \u001b[4m\u001b[22mGROUP1\u001b[24m[\u001b[4m,GROUP2,...\u001b[24m[\u001b[4m,GROUPN\u001b[24m]]]\u001b[m\r\n           A list of supplementary groups which the user is also a member\u001b[m\r\n           of. Each group is separated from the next by a comma, with no\u001b[m\r\n           intervening whitespace. The groups are subject to the same\u001b[m\r\n           restrictions as the group given with the \u001b[1m-g \u001b[22moption. The default\u001b[m\r\n           is for the user to belong only to the initial group. In addition\u001b[m\r\n           to passing in the -G flag, you can add the option \u001b[1mGROUPS \u001b[22mto the\u001b[m\r\n           file /etc/default/useradd which in turn will add all users to\u001b[m\r\n           those supplementary groups.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-h\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--help\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Display help message and exit.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-k\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--skel \u001b[4m\u001b[22mSKEL_DIR\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           The skeleton directory, which contains files and directories to\u001b[m\r\n           be copied in the user's home directory, when the home directory\u001b[m\r\n           is created by \u001b[1museradd\u001b[22m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           This option is only valid if the \u001b[1m-m \u001b[22m(or \u001b[1m--create-home\u001b[22m) option is\u001b[m\r\n           specified.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 93 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1363.826737, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K           If this option is not set, the skeleton directory is defined by\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 94 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1364.348214, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K           the \u001b[1mSKEL \u001b[22mvariable in /etc/default/useradd or, by default,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 95 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1364.368393, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K           /etc/skel.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 96 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1364.410558, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 97 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
