[1439.461789, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K           Do not create the user's home directory, even if the system wide\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 135 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1439.499575, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K           setting from /etc/login.defs (\u001b[1mCREATE_HOME\u001b[22m) is set to \u001b[4myes\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 136 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1439.518632, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 137 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1439.556855, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1m-N\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--no-user-group\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 138 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1439.593722, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K           Do not create a group with the same name as the user, but add the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 139 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1439.613213, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[1439.613564, "o", "           user to the group specified by the \u001b[1m-g \u001b[22moption or by the \u001b[1mGROUP\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 140 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1439.652166, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K"]
[1439.652537, "o", "           variable in /etc/default/useradd.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 141 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1439.827844, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 142 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1439.984327, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K           The default behavior (if the \u001b[1m-g\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m-N\u001b[22m, and \u001b[1m-U \u001b[22moptions are not\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 143 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1440.12228, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K           specified) is defined by the \u001b[1mUSERGROUPS_ENAB \u001b[22mvariable in\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 144 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1471.265866, "o", "\r\u001b[K           /etc/login.defs.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-o\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--non-unique\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           allows the creation of an account with an already existing UID.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           This option is only valid in combination with the \u001b[1m-u \u001b[22moption. As a\u001b[m\r\n           user identity serves as key to map between users on one hand and\u001b[m\r\n           permissions, file ownerships and other aspects that determine the\u001b[m\r\n           system's behavior on the other hand, more than one login name\u001b[m\r\n           will access the account of the given UID.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-p\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--password \u001b[4m\u001b[22mPASSWORD\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           defines an initial password for the account. PASSWORD is expected\u001b[m\r\n           to be encrypted, as returned by \u001b[1mcrypt \u001b[22m(3). Within a shell script,\u001b[m\r\n           this option allows to create efficiently batches of users.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Without this option, the new account will be locked and with no\u001b[m\r\n           password defined, i.e. a single exclamation mark in the\u001b[m\r\n           respective fi"]
[1471.266167, "o", "eld of /etc/shadow. This is a state where the user\u001b[m\r\n           won't be able to access the account or to define a password\u001b[m\r\n           himself.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1mNote:\u001b[22mAvoid this option on the command line because the password\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 167 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1475.405294, "o", "\r\u001b[K           (or encrypted password) will be visible by users listing the\u001b[m\r\n           processes.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           You should make sure the password respects the system's password\u001b[m\r\n           policy.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-r\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--system\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Create a system account.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           System users will be created with no aging information in\u001b[m\r\n           /etc/shadow, and their numeric identifiers are chosen in the\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1mSYS_UID_MIN\u001b[22m-\u001b[1mSYS_UID_MAX \u001b[22mrange, defined in /etc/login.defs,\u001b[m\r\n           instead of \u001b[1mUID_MIN\u001b[22m-\u001b[1mUID_MAX \u001b[22m(and their \u001b[1mGID \u001b[22mcounterparts for the\u001b[m\r\n           creation of groups).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Note that \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22mwill not create a home directory for such a\u001b[m\r\n           user, regardless of the default setting in /etc/login.defs\u001b[m\r\n           (\u001b[1mCREATE_HOME\u001b[22m). You have to specify the \u001b[1m-m \u001b[22moptions if you want a\u001b[m\r\n           home directory for a system account to be created.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           Note that this option will not update /etc/subuid and\u001b[m\r\n           /etc/subgid. You have to specify the \u001b[1m-F \u001b[22moptions if you want to\u001b[m\r\n           update the files for a system account to be created.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 190 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1476.689547, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-R\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--root \u001b[4m\u001b[22mCHROOT_DIR\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Apply changes in the \u001b[4mCHROOT_DIR\u001b[24m directory and use the\u001b[m\r\n           configuration files from the \u001b[4mCHROOT_DIR\u001b[24m directory. Only absolute\u001b[m\r\n           paths are supported.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-P\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--prefix \u001b[4m\u001b[22mPREFIX_DIR\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Apply changes to configuration files under the root filesystem\u001b[m\r\n           found under the directory \u001b[4mPREFIX_DIR\u001b[24m. This option does not chroot\u001b[m\r\n           and is intended for preparing a cross-compilation target. Some\u001b[m\r\n           limitations: NIS and LDAP users/groups are not verified. PAM\u001b[m\r\n           authentication is using the host files. No SELINUX support.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-s\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--shell \u001b[4m\u001b[22mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           sets the path to the user's login shell. Without this option, the\u001b[m\r\n           system will use the \u001b[1mSHELL \u001b[22mvariable specified in\u001b[m\r\n           /etc/default/useradd, or, if that is as well not set, the field\u001b[m\r\n           for the"]
[1476.689759, "o", " login shell in /etc/passwd remains empty.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-u\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--uid \u001b[4m\u001b[22mUID\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           The numerical value of the user's ID. This value must be unique,\u001b[m\r\n           unless the \u001b[1m-o \u001b[22moption is used. The value must be non-negative. The\u001b[m\r\n           default is to use the smallest ID value greater than or equal to\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 213 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1495.837793, "o", "\r\u001b[K           \u001b[1mUID_MIN \u001b[22mand greater than every other user.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           See also the \u001b[1m-r \u001b[22moption and the \u001b[1mUID_MAX \u001b[22mdescription.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-U\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--user-group\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Create a group with the same name as the user, and add the user\u001b[m\r\n           to this group.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           The default behavior (if the \u001b[1m-g\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m-N\u001b[22m, and \u001b[1m-U \u001b[22moptions are not\u001b[m\r\n           specified) is defined by the \u001b[1mUSERGROUPS_ENAB \u001b[22mvariable in\u001b[m\r\n           /etc/login.defs.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-Z\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--selinux-user \u001b[4m\u001b[22mSEUSER\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           defines the SELinux user for the new account. Without this\u001b[m\r\n           option, SELinux uses the default user. Note that the shadow\u001b[m\r\n           system doesn't store the selinux-user, it uses \u001b[1msemanage\u001b[22m(8) for\u001b[m\r\n           that.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m--selinux-range \u001b[4m\u001b[22mSERANGE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           defines the SELinux MLS range for the new account. Without this\u001b[m\r\n           option, SELinux uses the default range. Note that the shadow\u001b[m\r\n           system doesn't store the selinux-range, it uses \u001b[1msemanage\u001b[22m(8) for\u001b[m\r\n           that.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 236 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1499.034621, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n           This option is only valid if the \u001b[1m-Z \u001b[22m(or \u001b[1m--selinux-user\u001b[22m) option is\u001b[m\r\n           specified.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n   \u001b[1mChanging the default values\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       When invoked with only the \u001b[1m-D \u001b[22moption, \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22mwill display the\u001b[m\r\n       current default values. When invoked with \u001b[1m-D \u001b[22mplus other options,\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1museradd \u001b[22mwill update the default values for the specified options.\u001b[m\r\n       Valid default-changing options are:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-b\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--base-dir \u001b[4m\u001b[22mBASE_DIR\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           sets the path prefix for a new user's home directory. The user's\u001b[m\r\n           name will be affixed to the end of \u001b[4mBASE_DIR\u001b[24m to form the new\u001b[m\r\n           user's home directory name, if the \u001b[1m-d \u001b[22moption is not used when\u001b[m\r\n           creating a new account.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           This option sets the \u001b[1mHOME \u001b[22mvariable in /etc/default/useradd.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-e\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--expiredate \u001b[4m\u001b[22mEXPIRE_DATE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           sets the date on which newly created user accounts are disabled.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           This option sets the \u001b[1mEXPIRE \u001b[22mvariable in /etc/default/useradd.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 259 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1500.563012, "o", "\r\u001b[K       \u001b[1m-f\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--inactive \u001b[4m\u001b[22mINACTIVE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           defines the number of days after the password exceeded its\u001b[m\r\n           maximum age where the user is expected to replace this password.\u001b[m\r\n           See \u001b[1mshadow\u001b[22m(5)for more information.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           This option sets the \u001b[1mINACTIVE \u001b[22mvariable in /etc/default/useradd.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-g\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--gid \u001b[4m\u001b[22mGROUP\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           sets the default primary group for newly created users, accepting\u001b[m\r\n           group names or a numerical group ID. The named group must exist,\u001b[m\r\n           and the GID must have an existing entry.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           This option sets the \u001b[1mGROUP \u001b[22mvariable in /etc/default/useradd.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-s\u001b[22m, \u001b[1m--shell \u001b[4m\u001b[22mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           defines the default login shell for new users.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           This option sets the \u001b[1mSHELL \u001b[22mvariable in /etc/default/useradd.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNOTES\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The system administrator is responsible for placing the default user\u001b"]
[1500.563543, "o", "[m\r\n       files in the /etc/skel/ directory (or any other skeleton directory\u001b[m\r\n       specified in /etc/default/useradd or on the command line).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page useradd(8) line 282 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
